Parliament does not support Tymoshenko’s liberating amendment
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal the paragraph under which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The amendment, which would open the way to the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the proposal to commute the sentences for economic crimes.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly disadvantageous contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not final, the appeal of the convicted is to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko describes the verdict as a political vendetta of the regime, and the suspicion of bias in the court has also provoked the process in the West.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 from the Criminal Code, under which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes were needed to approve it.
