IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, originally with the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
IBM took over the name in 1924 - originally it was a brand used for branches of the company in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was the merger of four companies, the history of which dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous "stickers," i.e. the clocks recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new firm was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson led the company, sales doubled to $9 million and the company began to expand to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that his son, Thomas Watson Jr., succeeded him after nearly forty years in the boss’s chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM people and computers helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic PC that set the computer standard at the time, the IBM 5150, came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, it bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to devote itself fully to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has paid off over the past three years for IBM is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make smart use of technology in previously unplanned areas and improve the situation in, for example, transport or city administration.
For the business area, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which helps traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history at home.
It established its branch in what was then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM ČR, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Headquartered in Prague, Central and Eastern Europe, there is also a world-class voice recognition research team.
