How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold mostly only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled to the sea in the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both by the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand up to the queue overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
However, by far most often the Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages, which the Czechs took and this custom survives to this day.
Travel of Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right at the beginning of the 1990s, the visa requirement for neighboring Western European countries was lifted, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there at least for a while.
For example, in Paris, tours of Czechs slept in tents in parks, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guest house.
A typical feature of traveling Czechs at this time was bringing their own food, cans, sausages, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to finally buy the Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and average wages increased, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, tour operators have started to regularly prepare tours by charter flights since 1997, which has made air tours incredibly cheaper due to the possibility of contracting quantity discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first ever direct charter flight to the exotic was sent from the Czech Republic to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters have been flying with Czech tourists to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
At present, exotic countries are visited by about 100 thousand Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States revoked visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%), and for the first time in history, they spent more than CZK 15,000 per person for one foreign holiday, including costs at the place of stay.
