October 15, 2008 was a disaster.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of a small country of seven million decided on the biggest rescue in the history of its nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "Der UBS-Crash".
Up to 68 billion francs, or about 45 billion euros, were approved by politicians to save a standing big bank from bankruptcy.
How did this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem primarily in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of Switzerland's three large banks merged into a large group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for a small Switzerland during the merger - and it kept growing.
It helped that the two different banking predecessors of UBS were complementary: One rich but sleepy bank in Zurich with a focus on wealth management and poorer but more internationally involved.
Suddenly, internationalized investment bankers came in handy with a lot of money, with which they could spin a big roulette wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were the team of the future,” says banking expert Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intelligent, humble one who knows a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the man who manages the feelings around the stomach, who has gone all the way up from banking science."
But Ospel was said to have relied on Wuffli in the end.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: "I guess he thought his models were a reality," Geiger says.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, perhaps.
Pride preceded the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the meetings of executives at which Wuffli repeated the same slogan over and over again: To bring Goldman Sachs down from the throne.
The U.S. Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
It featured "League Tables", a waiting list that documents the success of the banks of the time.
In it, UBS tried to place it completely at the top.
She has already managed a few steps.
In foreign exchange and stock trading, she participated in the game at the very top.
But the corporate advisers who have been commissioned underline one weakness: In international interest-rate trade, in the bankers' "Fixed Income" speech, there is probably a great distance behind the largest banks.
UBS may have gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close the gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost her her her existence.
Hungry for growth, they invested both the bank itself and the fund founded by it to hedge risks in U.S. Subprime investments.
It developed into a massive machine that would repackage securities into U.S. mortgages and pass them on, but also keep the risks.
Even when other banks have long been looking for a way out.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the real estate market was on fire, UBS was buying there," says banking expert Geiger.
How great is the euphoria, how deep is the fall.
One manager after another had to leave when attempts to clean up were more difficult than thought.
Positions at UBS have become ejection seats and are swinging to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost unmanageable job.
He must find a strategy for the bank that all nearby business models have disappeared.
Banking expert Geiger already has an idea: An end to investment banking, concentration on wealth management, a return to Swiss roots.
The bank doesn’t (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is about to fade, so much is now clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Swiss Italian was seen as merely a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly broke up with its predecessor, Groebel.
Meanwhile, he has made a name for himself: he is to run UBS’s business for a long time, the Zurich bank said on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to restore the investment bank in the mid-1990s.
3500 seats will be removed.
But that won't be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does he want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking himself.
In public, however, he says only that he and his wife will first find an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
