In many places, field ravens are considered "problem birds": However, these highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of cities, experts say.
Some like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the image of the city for centuries, yet in some municipalities complaints of residents to the dirt and noise caused by animals are accumulating.
However, there is still no way to deal with "problem birds".
Wild boars can no longer be driven out of cities, experts said at the first symposium on crows in East Frisian Leere.
There, experts from all over the federal territory consulted on possible ways forward.
Look for alternatives in cities
Conservationists also derived urban problems from the exodus of specially protected field ravens: the use of chemistry in agriculture is likely to be increasingly destroying traditional areas for life.
Persecution, growing buildings and cutting down typical trees to nest birds make life difficult.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 nesting pairs are located in Soest, Westphalia, in the northwest, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen, and in Leer.
There, a 2005 controversial project of mass killing of crows in a rural district generated negative headlines.
Critics have called the capture of animals into bird traps and the killing of sticks particularly brutal.
"Normal banishment, timidity, brings nothing", so much was discovered by the urbanist and landscape designer Werner Kl?ver of Leer.
Removing nests by spraying water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser of Lahr in Baden-Wuerttemberg.
