Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund’s powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that make you dizzy.
One piece of advice at a time: Carefully tear out this page and make it a bookmark.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund’s novel narrative, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - in moments when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "anti-historical work".
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as a "book about what it was like". It mainly deals with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the wartime experiences of 20 men and women, more or less dozen, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fates, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classic historical novels.
It modifies the notion that World War I was all about the gruesome trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book solve the problems of falling bee nests on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, this is a very moving read.
War engulfs people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts in the distance and you are a woman who is at home with your children, will you run away or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," remarked Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other published materials.
Descriptions of their lives may sound scary and engaging, but thanks to the inclusion of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them talk about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Substitutions, everywhere substitutes."
