The Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another young man who presented his anti-immigrant views online.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to a July killing rampage that left 77 people dead in Norway, attended his first public hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was certainly not lonely in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to get them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, that it was enough for the researchers to simply use the site’s advertising to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for with absolute accuracy, something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, and they focused their attention on them and sent them advertisements, but instead of inviting them to join a newly formed group or offering them some diet products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about their level of education, their relationship to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men, spurred by rising rates of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health problems to social trends hiding behind status updates, wall posts, and "like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides three different data on a daily basis, which makes this social network literally an "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic works in the name of which the word Facebook occurs, increased from five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"Previously, when you wanted to do a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to go to a party where they’d never let you go,” Bartlett says.
"This is all Facebook is tearing down - you're just going straight to them."
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken output on Facebook were much more likely to have an alcoholism problem than students who kept quiet about the topic.
Moren suggests that students' peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
"The problem can't be solved if you can't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children that we would not otherwise have had a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The site's information team has produced statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010 and the nation's satisfaction rate (mainly using information they had access to - proponents of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available for research to others as well).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, you need to provide the site with your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
