A lie could destroy entire careers and cloud the stability of many countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of using his campaign funds to try to conceal his illegitimate relationship.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that rallied around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
It's all just stories of cheating at school and university.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers, only to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and deception is acceptable.
How many frauds do we encounter?
Studies show that in one day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first meeting.
Determining lies, or "recognizing lies," is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or business reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar to, say, a charade in which a person shouts, "I got you." The recognition of deception is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been disproved.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're stuttering, stuttering, blushing, or sewing.
But don’t assume that it’s difficult to spot and spot the liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years amassing scientific knowledge from a vast and evolving industry related to the recognition of lies, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can be of great help in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, holding interviews, negotiating, or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them relax in vigilance, channel their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "self-centered" lies - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (although the lies they tell are usually "outrageous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called “initial observation.”
Thanks to him, he will have later findings to compare with.
Note the posture of the subject, his laughter, working with the voice.
You should know if someone routinely taps their feet all the time so that you don’t unjustifiably accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to determine the clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
But consider it only as a warning sign, not as evidence of a lie.
Lying people can stop moving the upper half of their body as they try to remember their imaginary story, they can turn the tips of their shoes towards the door, lean toward the exit, significantly change posture, or show "relief after the conversation" - exaggerated relief respite and change of position when confession is difficult behind them.
Interviewers will often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like after it is over.
Also, consider the subject’s language.
There is a famous story about how Scott Peterson once misspelled and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which launched a nationwide search for her body.
Lying individuals can also express themselves in a measured manner: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady...Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of "relieving language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
In such an answer, we do not learn much facts, and often it is another warning signal.
There is no magic to reveal every lie, but it is possible to acquire the skills to track down a lie.
Using these skills, a person will have a better chance of not fooling some liar and cheater in his personal and professional life.
