Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment decreased, and with it the economy
2011 will go down in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, which calls itself the government of change. This government brought with it high expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth and even a decrease in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the possibilities of growth of the state economy, they are responsible for a decrease in economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historic decrease of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to a damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed, and on the remaining 21.07% was found partial damage. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increased increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment rose by approximately 9.28%, and between July and August the average.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps that have been taken at the public policy level.
“We are seeing rising unemployment linked to various factors, including loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints as a result of legislation passed by Congress to combat money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn, invest or use them for anything,” he stressed.
Stopping the Migration
López Cervantes said the demographic factor also contributed to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of the difficult entry and because even if these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job, so people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising," he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state work without paying benefits to the social security administration.
Other features of the labor market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory, wages from the whole country are the lowest, as reported by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 pesetas by September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 saw the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, with foreign direct investment reaching $630,697 in January-June, down 87.74% from $5,143,312 in the same period the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government lists investments of 17,280 million pesetas per year.
Debts
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. Until November, no profits were recorded from debt, not in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés pointed to a lack of managerial skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, stated that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really minuscule during this year. We need to work hard to regain the land we lost this year. In 2012, we need to double the effort, there was no harmonization of the efforts of all of us, and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let's hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year had halted the state's economy and restricted its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamism that would allow to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year we were well below the expected forecasts," he said.
Redefining the Mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we observe that work is being done. We believe that a long-term plan should be prepared in which the goals and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilized," he said.
The work ahead of us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there have been some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He stated that the current administration has shown progress when it comes to conducting public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that the work done here is visible, and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
