Court Approves 'End of Analogous Broadcasting' in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected the constitutional action brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which wants to hasten the so-called "turning off analog signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. He stated that the necessary eight votes were not found to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued a decree outlining the individual steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed, because the qualified majority of eight votes needed to allow the court to express its opinion on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid, was not reached.
The draft judgment drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero presents the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of all issues related to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel). This violates the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exception of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to combat the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive could not structure measures through general standards to prepare the public administration.
"I don't think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulator", and he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, with better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that postponing the change would delay the benefits of digitalisation, which requires a decision on a matter of public interest, since digitalisation has not only a technical dimension, but also "affects economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he stressed, these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It includes a number of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the government of the state".
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to the digital system and had done so through their governments, even though they had highly specialised technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it was not possible for the government, by issuing a disapproving decree that to some extent interferes with the powers of Congress, to bring into the administration the observance of laws prepared by legislative power.
In Michoacán analyze the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to the data published by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent. So far, 879 votes out of 6074 electoral districts have not been counted.
The vote-by-vote option appeared in this year's elections in Michoacán, where, according to data published by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent, and it has not yet been counted by 879 votes from a total of 6074 electoral districts.
In this context, the chair of the General Council of the Electoral Institute in Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral authority approved a number of measures that should harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not officially confirm his political constitution or his State Electoral Code or the Electoral Justice Act, because the state congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force was due to expire during this parliamentary term, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected to publish them within the set deadline in the Official State Gazette Act, stating that he had some objections to them.
On 9 November, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative power and declared the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" because he has no right to "either approve or veto them".
When asked about the possibility of a "vote by vote" census, María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, with the approval of the relevant measures by the General Council of the IEM, it would be possible for both the partial and the overall census to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, a partial counting of votes, of one or more election packages, will be possible under the following conditions: election results do not agree; there is no record of the counting of votes and the calculation in the relevant box or it is not available to the President; or if there have been errors and obvious violations of election results.
In addition, a total recount of votes in all ballot boxes will be possible if there is evidence to suggest that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request from the party and/or coalition representative who proposed the candidate in second place appears at the beginning of the session.
A total recount will also be possible if, after a proper tally, it is found that the difference between the probable winner and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, and also whenever there is an explicit request from a political party whose candidate finished in second place. In this case, electoral packages for which a partial tally has been made will be eliminated.
It should be mentioned that in such a situation there is an election in Morelia, where, according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second places is less than 0.16%, although 129 out of 923 electoral districts have not yet been added.
