A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that is holding the country over the abyss of economic disaster.
Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face a crisis that is holding the country over the abyss of economic disaster and that has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The presidential palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm to him that he can form a government.
It is expected to introduce a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult stage," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that obstacles were being overcome.
"The framework is now well marked," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which has pushed its debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders, only to restore Italy's compromised credibility.
Due to market volatility, interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity have exceeded the 7 percent threshold, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to ask for rescue.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organisation Confindustria, told reporters after the meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this predicament.
Monti's hopes for success have been greatly increased thanks to the support of PDL's Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now, a number of its members have opposed a government with a technocratic majority formed by Monti.
Support of Parliament
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could spell disaster.
Monti opened talks with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organizations on Monday.
The round ends Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who allowed a very quick move in response to the crisis.
After a short decline at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, the interest rates on Italian bonds have returned to a critical limit, reacting to the uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister will reap success.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is worth 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the scope of the eurozone’s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next election, which is scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will give him time only to implement reforms, and then call early elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that the government must be composed only of experts to bring Italy out of the difficulties the country has come into because of financial pressure.
