We will try to show the best show with diverse songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose what songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and we'd be in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much has been given to us and we are moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We’re lucky to be able to see the places we’ve always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the creation of the genre of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which all the greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It’s surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to arise from one city at a time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think that firstly we are all lucky to be still in this world and secondly the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to that we have managed to open musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We believe in each other, we appreciate each other’s music and I don’t think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect music and what you gave it. You must not get carried away by being famous, rock stars. Neither of us ever really cared.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something great in the beginning.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy, how incredible I was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, to have fun with him.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
National band Las Robertas will be tasked with launching the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as opening act?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter?
That's the question for Eddie Vedder, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk all night about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've always felt a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I think of bands that I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came together at the same time, and if that’s true today, it’s something great, because it’s music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly bleak character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent just that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make bleak music.
Peru:
Fujimori hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is now under medical control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will undergo tests in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases, where they should find out why he hurts and why he is losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could receive a pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, the former president himself does not wish the pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times due to cancer of the tongue, lost 18 kilograms and these problems were accompanied by other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, cyst on the pancreas, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor named.
Fujimori has served his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his reign.
Mujica to visit Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday, aiming to achieve an expansion of trade between the two nations and touch on the political themes of the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit full of meetings with representatives of politics, business and representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan presidential office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political issues between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France, which occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that will continue to be tax havens would be excluded from the international community, a statement that provoked a backlash from Uruguay and a consultation with the ambassador to that European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries. It has had an information exchange agreement with that Latin American country since January this year to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concretize fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) blacklist, to which there are countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of tax cooperation.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has boosted trade between the two countries.
Bearded plumber running in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the villain Bowser, but has never yet appeared in 3D: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which is coming to stores around the world this month, was created from the beginning to take advantage of all the features offered by the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows you to play three-dimensional games without having to use glasses.
"Mario is a character who has to tell how stereoscopy is supposed to work without glasses," said Omar Álvarez, a Nintendo press officer in Spain, during a video game presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game created specifically for this medium", because until now successful images such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of already existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesman said that in addition to being 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "available" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple", the task of which is to attract less skilled users.
Once you have overcome this level, you can embark on the "second round" on the levels of the game, which are more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose real time between "aggressive D" or one that affects only the depth of the action. But it will be necessary to play in 3D, in order to overcome all sorts of challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This new arrival of Super Mario in 3D is also expected with the return of the character to the portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo plays into the notes of those who follow the saga and repeats the successful formula from the previous episodes. It consists in the fact that the plumber of the bearded man will have to go through dangerous mined platforms to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find news in the moves, in the neighborhood, in disguise and also among enemies, the "playful" Luigi will also appear.
Colom approved Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he has taken steps to extradite former President Alfons Portillo, who is to be held accountable in the United States for a $70 million US laundering conspiracy.
Thus ends a process aimed at getting Guatemala to respond to a request from a northern country to extradite Portillo in order to try him.
At a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was consistent with the independence of the judicial and executive powers and that he was mindful that the criminal court had already ordered extradition.
He assured that during his mandate he had "not interfered" with court decisions and had allowed all the extraditions that had reached his desk.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's move marks a step of execution after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to lead a trial against the former president who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala is resolved and human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzlement of $120 million at the Department of Defense at the time of his presidency, a process that preceded extradition, but the Department of Public Affairs appealed and brought the case back into play.
Trinijove helped 6,000 young people in a state of danger
The organization was created to help children without education, so that they would not find themselves on the fringes of society.
The balance of the first 25 years of the Trinijove social support organization is very important: 6,000 young people who were threatened with social exclusion received help. The organization has been helping them to overcome difficult situations for 25 years.
To this must be added the long hundreds of jobs that have been obtained for this social group.
Yesterday's anniversary also served to present the balance sheet as part of the ceremony, which took place in the former Fabra i Coats factory premises and which was attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in the Trinitat Vella neighborhood in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with low education, without work, struggling with drug addiction or in a situation where they could fall into social exclusion.
Yesterday’s meeting in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of representatives of organizations and institutions that have cooperated with the association over the past 25 years.
The diverse political representation, at the time of the election, showed the uniform character of the work carried out by Trinijov.
Along with President Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, former Socialist Education Advisor, Ernest Maragall, and former Deputy Mayor and current Eco-Socialist Councillor Ricardo Goma attended the ceremony.
The big hall of Fabra and Coats was also attended by the current Social Welfare and Family Advisor, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of Social Work at La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas said that Triniove originated at a very difficult time and that today also offers a number of obstacles, but added that the work that the association has brought to this day "is a good foundation".
The president cited Trinikov as an example of how it is possible to combat adverse circumstances and how to give courage to people in difficult situations.
"The crisis is nothing new for this organization and the work it does," he said.
There was an eviction of the seized house, in which gigantic parties were held
Invaders take possession of 11 of 13 apartments in Balmes, 51
12 occupiers left the house yesterday at noon without resisting
The nightmare of the neighbors at 51 Balmes Street is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they were illegally living in yesterday at noon, where they organized gigantic parties that woke the neighbors. They left the building by order of the court and without the need for the police to intervene.
After the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a repetition of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," the administrator said.
The occupiers, who took 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all electrical and partly also water equipment, in addition, they painted the walls and left behind garbage of all kinds, especially cans after alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held in the first three apartments, lasting up to two days and waking up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that sales had fallen by 80% during the time the building was occupied.
The owner of the disco emphasizes that the occupants of the building made it unfair competition because they sold drinks for 3 euros, while the disco costs 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment business had to respond to complaints from neighbors due to noise, but the problems were not caused by visitors to the discotheque, but by the residents of the seized house, and especially those who attended the parties held here, whose frequency and intensity has increased in recent weeks, according to the angry residents of the neighborhood.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that they even agreed with the owner of the building and had been forgiving her rent for nine months.
City police have also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbors over the past weeks about the situation.
Last week, the president of the People's Party's municipal group PP in the city hall, Alberto Fernández Díaz, demanded that "the building be immediately evicted, thus putting an end to the problems of civil coexistence suffered by neighbors and the destruction of the area".
The leader of the people explained that only one floor had been taken before the summer, but in recent months the occupiers have reached all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them there have even been thefts.
He added: “We need to end impunity and be consistent when it comes to the acts against civil responsibility that took place in the building.”
Yesterday, the city police also cleared the building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police entered building 35 on Mont-ral Street after being summoned by neighbors who saw four people entering the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of the announcement of the proceedings, which involves more than a controversy about fees
The municipal tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, during the heyday of the already defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The flyer defined the mountain as a large park of the metropolitan city of Barcelona.
What’s more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York’s Central Park.
After the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park has returned to the minds of many as the top border of Barcelona. The Catalan capital is one of the few that do not focus on the north - south axis, but up (up) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collseroly as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of Yogi Bear.
This was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, records the idea of the park.
Either that, or someone's trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and on the basis of reflection on the city, this issue becomes the central topic of all Barcelona architects.
It's as old a topic as when two members of this old caste of chosen ones shake hands when they meet in an elevator.
It was this act that created one of the rare coincidences between what the three Barcelona architects and the pre-graduate university professors thought.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure is justified.
According to Roldan, after the question of the bay side began, "it is also necessary" to discuss the "mountain side", so that Ildefons Cerd's speech on green apples was not completed.
“We have to start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its high availability.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "Gateway to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as demarcations of zones where it is possible to operate".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience from the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" posing "some dangers".
The danger arising from the "uncertainty presented today by the project of a public place" after the experience of the 1980s, which had in the area of the Forum "its swan singing".
The first concern is the very definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
"To define something is to take the next step", that is, to go one step further.
"It is necessary to keep in mind the new urban planning and planning tools, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster".
If we focus in more detail on the question, Modol believes that the valley slope of Collserola can be "considered a park", but not the Barcelona part, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "cannot end up in a garbage dump", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his Bureau to intervene in the project from "the first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of cul-de-sac that allows architects to get involved in the debate, but he "doubts" that it should be precisely this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the name to this game is complex, since Collserola's global vision is missing in the background for the tender: "There have been 16 tenders that deal with all the axes of the mountain - the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that looks at the area and understands it as a whole".
This causes at least he, applied to all 16 selection procedures.
Otherwise, the project of one gate may allude to the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
In his opinion, the town hall should guarantee that the zone immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide a zone of equipment along the entire length, which would ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
Casino apologizes to Jonas Larrazábal, who will be released
After 72 days of imprisonment, legal counsel Cadino Red granted pardon to Mayor Monterrey's brother in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonás Larrazábal has been in prison for 72 days and will now be released after being pardoned by Casino Red's legal representative before the Second Criminal Court in the district, which dealt with the racketeering case in which Mayor Monterrey's brother was indicted.
Following the assassination of Casino Royale, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García posted a series of photos and videos of Manuel Jonás asking him to pay an economic quota to allow the town hall in Monterrey to operate illegally in a betting house.
After the public prosecution, the State Prosecutor's Office launched a criminal prosecution of the brother of a panistic mayor. On September 2, he was detained and imprisoned for 30 days.
Then, after 4 hours spent in front of Public Ministry Agent No. 3 for property crimes, he was transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the state capital.
He remained at this location for the next 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued, and a Public Ministry agent disproved the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On 19 October, he was transferred to the Cadereyta Criminal Court on suspicion of blackmailing the owners of the Casino Red with an amount of one and a half million pesos. However, he remained only a few hours in prison with moderate supervision because he was threatened with death.
The leaders allowed him to remain in the city cells at San Nicolás de los Garza during the trial.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who stated that after almost two months of investigation, enough evidence had been collected to prove Jonas' guilt. Among the evidence, for example, the payment of 1.5 million pesos to casino representatives in exchange for the promise that the operation would be made possible.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to judge José Luis Pecino and asked for a pardon for the brother of the mayor of the region. Based on this, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal hearing, the representative of the Public Ministry assigned to this court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez if the damages had been repaired and who of the associates decided to grant the pardon. But the lawyer made it clear that the name would remain secret.
On the basis of the official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal. No complaint can be filed in the trial that has been conducted against him. Nor is it possible to seek damages or punishment.
After a trial with a legal representative around 3:50 p.m., the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Breton.
The court secretary, Jorge Yanez, arrived at the prison in the city of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonas that he had been granted an official pardon and that his case had been deferred to the archives.
He also informed him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jacome gave details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident, which killed Secretary of the Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people, show that the helicopter hit the terrain with full force, without the pilot having a chance to try to make a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jacome, Communications and Transport Secretary, said the pilot had stated before the plane took off that the climate conditions made the flight possible.
"Parts appearing suggest that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, wings entangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost its hull".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he said that based on the investigation carried out in the area of impact, no components were found on the ground.
"The search revealed that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft hit land as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get the results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services stated that at the moment of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that this was a normal overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jacome enumerated six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at takeoff, accordingly, the aircraft is advancing towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico there were noticeable layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds, the crew were looking for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The pattern of dispersion of the aircraft remains indicates that the helicopter was solid at the time of impact on the mainland.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident to indicate that there was an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show images that probably broke down along the mentioned route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search around the accident, in an area larger than the demarcation area, the remains of the helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still intact.
Mexican Institute of Health Insurance Launches Research on the Gene That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of National Remembrance
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "Obesity genetics in children and adolescents" will allow to get results regarding overweight.
In a report, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit at the 21st Century National Health Center’s Specialized Hospital, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists, and social workers had been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without authorization, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where each council will be tested by minors from 8 o'clock.
He stressed that the research began at the Sports Center Cuauhtémoc (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity has also been carried out at the Sports Center Nezahualcóyolt (East of Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are collected, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors to Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and a family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are made anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify the genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflected health officials’ concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, there was an increase in obesity in boys by 77% and in girls by 47%. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight," said an expert from IMSS.
He stated that one of the reasons for searching for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they get an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thereby determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He noted that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that an individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
For now, the information is confidential, doctors give it in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children getting the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, all-day sitting in front of the TV, and the use of means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Excess weight is also caused by a large caloric intake, that is, greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If paving were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, adding that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavements were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even a complete elimination of them.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Potholes, which he delivered during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should create a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and at high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight, which are called asphaltenes, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called mortars. Together, they give asphalt its typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, the expert on chemical engineering pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt liner, formed by small pebbles embedded in the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to decompose well.
If it was modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer, called the mantle, is placed on the asphalt liner, consisting of fine stone, i.e. sand also embedded in the asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt liner and ensure road friction.
Since it will be exposed to a lot of stress as part of the paving, the cladding must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken with the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inward and it is difficult to get out, this causes all layers of paving to soften and thus create potholes.
He explained that during the creation of potholes, the film of the shell is damaged first and only then the asphalt liner is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one moment, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of paving must correspond to the load of vehicles and must be guaranteed not to exceed this load. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent occurrence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that we still have a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
