That was the job of a Cali resident who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
Cali's fingerprint expert went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4 last year, a CTI fingerprint expert in Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of Farc's supreme leader: "Alphonse Cano", through a comparison of fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working in the CTI department, this week was the turn of Eliazar González, a man from Puerta Tejada who has been working in the field of forensic research for 21 years.
Early in his career, González worked at the Chocó City Hall, where he often had to pierce the forest for more than five days to get to the site where the bodies needed to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital Valle and after completing the relevant courses, he began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of rubbing the skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against the aforementioned Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to take his clothes with him for a minimum of three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night, he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he would have to identify the two corpses and that he suspected that one of them was the man who was leading the oldest guerilla in the world, so they asked him to take a card with the fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the scene of the body, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But prints don't lie.
Along with a galton magnifying glass, ink, and a transplanter, and a light, Eliazar began to compare the date records of the corpse with those of the card.
The eye did not disappoint him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, a Puerto Tejada-born man was commissioned to confirm to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he was indeed the supreme commander of Farc.
Search for Stops
For the dactyloscope of Sijín de Cali, the recognition given to Eliazar González by President Juan Manuel Santos at the press conference of the operational service against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our jobs.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, that can play a key role in criminal decision-making.
In addition to identifying corpses, these people assist in researching crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When they get caught, a lot of delinquents present false papers or don't have papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The investigator told that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the house wall in the house, because at this place the thief leaned to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not meant to take fingerprints, but in this case we could get a full handprint and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also confirm or disprove a suspicion in a murder case.
Recently, a man was found dead with bottles of alcohol around him.
The investigation found that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and the imprint on the bottle actually confirmed this.
Although it is impossible to 100% confirm that he was really the murderer, it is clear that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint expert explained that fingerprints are "wiped off objects using chemical or physical reactive substances".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used for their collection.
Then the fingerprints are sent to Asif, which is a database of offenders, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are currently many Colombians whose data is not recorded anywhere," said the expert from the CTI.
He explained that not everything is as it is shown in the CSI television program.
Just as everything that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch has traces.
However, if it can be used, an appropriate comparison must be made.
