Only 9% of Canadians actually accept the opportunity to talk to a doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make decisions in that sense.
This is one of the conclusions of a large-scale report by the Royal Canadian Society, which involved six experts working in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This commission recommends that the government amend criminal law to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia if this option appears necessary for a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
In the beginning, experts cite a recent survey by the independent Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
Although Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has given rise to a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death.”
Medicalization yes or no, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts with the mandate of the Royal Canadian Society tell us.
And despite the wish to die at home that most Canadians have, 68.6% of them die in hospital.
This average applies to the whole of Canada, while in the province of Quebec this figure is the highest with 86% of people dying in hospital.
Regarding the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report draw conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything about criminal law regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
According to experts who have also controlled all countries where these approaches are legalized or are not considered a criminal case, there is no evidence that this decriminalization is causing any abuse in the application, i.e. in the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide to persons inappropriate or disapproving.
In contrast, Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, confirmed more cases of these abuses in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is also being carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal".
“Assisted suicide is also carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians are in favour of euthanasia.
Recall that according to a poll conducted by the Angus Reid Forum in 2010, 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favor of euthanasia because they believe it will allow people at the end of their lives to ease their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean sending a message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are worth less.
When it comes to people who practice assisted suicide, 41% of those surveyed believe they should not be prosecuted.
In the matter of maintaining or discontinuing patient care, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
They also suggest in the list of their recommendations that it should be stated in criminal law that withdrawal from treatment for which there is a legally confirmed refusal is not punishable.
The Commission of Experts also requires that medical professionals be educated to respect the obligation to refuse treatment at the end of life without fear of prosecution.
In the matter of palliative care, the Commission urgently requires governments, health institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, even in cases of cancer.
Finally, in the matter of palliative or terminal relief already widely used in Canadian health facilities, the Commission calls for it to be considered euthanasia at a time when it no longer serves to reduce physical pain and to be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations of other experts
Some medical law experts have already expressed their reservations about the conclusions of the Royal Canadian Society’s expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in medical law, qualified the position of expert-signatories of the report as "extreme" among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
“This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over the age of 18 could ask to be helped to commit suicide,” said Pierre Deschamps, who studied the report.
Deschamps also underlines that it seems as if the authors of the report place the autonomy of the person above all other values that shape the social fabric of society.
Because "in society, he says, there are warning signs and restrictions".
Medical law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong objections to the conclusions of the report, which she qualified as a 'manifesto for euthanasia'."
Margaret Somerville, herself a member of the Royal Canadian Society, especially doubts the data of the report regarding the absence of misconduct in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, i.e. in the Netherlands and the U.S. state of Oregon.
