Entry of the Golden Rule on Balanced Budget into the Constitution
The government of Austria’s grand coalition of social democrats and Christian democrats decided on Tuesday to include the “golden rule” of budget policy in the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade by Austria’s rating agencies (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the conclusion of a ministerial meeting in a situation where the Austrian public debt, with its 74.6%, is well above the criterion of no more than 60% set by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year," argued Vice-Chancellor and Foreign Minister, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus follows up on the request of the Euro Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State and Government strongly requested that the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of a balance of public accounts be enshrined in the Constitution or in a law of equal value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the federal states, as well as municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The aim is to bring public debt under the 60% criterion of the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
