Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balance sheets or under emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural for an election meeting to be an opportunity to think about such deposits and a place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will only succeed if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are explored.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will cause a doubling of the demand for electricity by 2050 if we do not want a significant part of the world's population to be deprived of an important part of life.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be tackled in order to continue producing electricity, while not forgetting the need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a theme that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The accident at Fukushima does not affect any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear power.
However, this is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor in Switzerland, which considers it right to build only the last generation of power plants.
On the contrary, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, are continuing with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by resuming the construction of one power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island power plant accident.
If the German model based on renewable energies is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind power, which consumes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to the irregularity of the wind, which makes CO2 emissions and prices of Danish electricity higher by 65% or 50%, respectively, than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbors will pay an electricity bill 40% higher than the payment of French households.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of keeping industry on national territory, French businesses enjoy the benefits of Europe’s cheapest electricity.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the re-industrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
The price that the great majority of the French refuse to pay, just as they fundamentally do not oppose this energy, as public opinion polls show.
Let us recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 downstream jobs.
The heavily exporting sector has attracted a large number of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
Should France decide to leave the nuclear power plant, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose the 6 billion euros a year it receives for exporting nuclear equipment and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to operate for 60 years while its manufacturer was scheduled to fail?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magical source for energy production, indeed, that there is no diabolical one.
The development of low-CO2 installations, nuclear installations and installations using renewable energy sources by the French industrial group AREVA testifies to the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is an absolute necessity to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Office for Nuclear Safety, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island occurred under normal traffic conditions and was left without human casualties and environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama was caused by reactor concepts and inexcusable human errors.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the crash was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, causing the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident just as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers, the EPR reactor represents a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all those wishing to build a nuclear power plant consider it, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift offered to competitors of the AREVA Group and EDF, and paving the way for them to take a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solutions for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and machinations dominate the debate so crucial to our country's economic, social and financial situation.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various angles - the congestion of police, courts and administrations subjected to the policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of "land of human rights" that France boasts.
More recently, it was administrative harassment of foreign students, which became topical when the Interior Minister (see Libération of 23 May) declared that France “does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses”.
But so far it has rarely been discussed from an economic point of view.
It should be said that there is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right in this area.
On the right, Jacques Chirac declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where there are 2 million migrant workers" and on the left Michel Rocard, when in 1990 he said that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fear of an invasion by hordes of Polish plumbers into French territory was shared to the right and left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity that we deign to provide to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to banality, stating that common development will allow us to solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may be valid in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published paper Synthesizing the Latest Knowledge on Immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.): there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages, and employment in immigrant countries.
Restrictions on immigration are crippling growth and damaging employment.
Concerns about the impact caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are far more a complement than a surrogate for French workers by doing jobs in sectors with a shortage of workers.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between French and migrants are causing immigrant arrivals to have a positive effect on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would result in a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
It does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries at an average of 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that in Germany, one immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (income minus expenses) of EUR 150000 to public budgets throughout his or her life.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed his wish to go for the missing percentages of growth "with priced teeth".
These teeth used to repel immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, even though it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some people may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to make the choice and carry it out in the most direct way possible.
However, it is known from Napoleon that it was easy to think.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an “instrument of oppression,” as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy demands much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of separation and control of powers, education, the Enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it has been the same since the beginning of the crisis of politics and democracy.
Admitting the error of the Greek yes-no referendum in this regard will have the value of a double revelation: revealing the necessity of a great return of political power, but also revealing the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We can gain nothing if we demand a series of national referendums organised as necessary and disorganised.
Bianco exposed to a European absolutist monarch or jump with his feet bound into the void of nationalist depth: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - and we would not know where to stop any more - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe, bowing to the dictates of the markets and credit rating agencies, which suffers from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
The management of the European project of democratic sovereignty urgently needs to be returned.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of the rule of the markets and prepare the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will presuppose decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After having long fought against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is strongly demanding a European economic government.
So be it.
But to think this without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must take on a new phase of European construction.
In order to be a republic in France, it was necessary to be a republican.
A revolution in interests could not be enough.
This lesson continues.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic and genuine European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans in order to build Europe.
