The terrorist front extends from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the ties between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-standing suspicions that there are ties between the Al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (AQMI) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's deputy foreign minister Abdelkader Messahel even admitted that Algiers had "gained confidence" about this from now on.
"The way the two organizations operate and intelligence reports show that there is a great deal of cooperation between them," he explained without further specifying.
Paris seems to have similar analyses.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January 2010 could help illuminate the connecting bridges.
After being kidnapped by members of the AQMI from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the following day at the same time as several of their captors in an operation carried out by special French troops.
In the rubble after the raid, French and Nigerian investigators were to find several phones with chips belonging to terrorists.
The Terrorist Axis
The analysis of the calls carried out leads to several people in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers: one leads to a Nigerian who has long resided in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria that is the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a person said to be close to the AQI and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for more convincing evidence before we start talking about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram".
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and that it is showing itself more and more actively,” Nigerian investigator Kunle Amuwo said in a statement.
In recent months, this “support” has become more and more evident in the development and manifestation of Boko Haram or its operational procedures, which now include human casualties or increasingly complex explosive devices of the same design as those used by AQMI.
The international community, led by Washington, has since put pressure on Nigeria to take into account the problems raised by Boko Haram.
In fact, the Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened mystics of little interest.
Rapid success
The Boko Haram sect was founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around the mosque, school and fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf. Boko Haram, which in haoussa means "Western education is a sin", approves the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, such a connection has been a rapid success.
The sect politicizes and demands strict adherence to Islamic sharia law, while its followers launch a struggle against the central government.
These people focus first on churches, bars, and offices.
In 2009, Boko Haram supporters become extremely active, multiplying their attacks against police stations.
As usual, the government’s response is the same.
The army encircles the city, resulting in 800 deaths.
The founder of the sect, Mohammed Yusuf, is caught and killed in prison.
Since then, the group has become radicalized and is leaving its post in the north.
At Christmas 2010, he carried out an assassination in the city of Jos, killing 80 people, followed by another in the capital Abuja.
In June, it is again in Abuja, where Boko Haram will attack the police headquarters in its first suicide attack.
And in August, the local UN office will be the first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which should lead from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, now worries all security specialists.
Now that al-Qaeda of the Islamic Maghreb has surrounded Mali and the Iger and the Somalis of the Al-Shabaab movement are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new danger to the continent.
Last week in Nigeria, in an interview with President Goodluck, Jonathan Alain Juppé said that France is on alert and ready to "hand over all information".
