Nord Stream, the new port of entry of Russian gas to Europe
The long-distance Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has begun to operate.
It must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday’s inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned the control around the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe every year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania region.
The second pipeline, which has to be completed by the end of 2012, will enable a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, which is equal to the total French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of a victory.
Poland and the Baltic states strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being routed by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some of their power: the possibility of putting pressure on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the “new German-Soviet pact”, referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained more certainty in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created rifts between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Just five years ago, Russia succeeded in pushing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-intensive Western states, whose deposits are coming to an end.
“This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” said Fillon at the opening ceremony, demonstrating the point at which large gas contracts are a matter of both political and economic importance.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom’s leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical feat.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields from the time of World War II.
"For security reasons, almost 100 of them had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens M?ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations on its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see Russian state society settle permanently off their coasts.
“In the event of a fault, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,” explains Jens M?ller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, because the welds were designed so that leaks arise once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline from the outside is controlled by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the interior of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
It will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts at the destination for three days at a speed of 3 m/s.
The pipeline was designed to last 50 years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
Gazprom remains in the lead, holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company all its gas transport capacity for five years under a contract that can be renewed.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the volume of gas it transports,” explains Jens M?ller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs rose to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned to them, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the exit gate of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
As of Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine - branded notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded fifty years ago, wants to once again provide the joy of writing.
It brings the scent of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves of faded white color as if aged over time.
Moleskine, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decides to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes up the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (imitation of leather), which is used, for example, to adjust the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly regarded by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has brought back an old and forgotten item that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become a brand leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from secret production from the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to assemble some artificial portrait of the buyer, because the notebook will captivate the businessman as well as the student or professionals.
The image of Moleskine’s notebook is that its owners are people cosmopolitan, cultivated and open minded.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and through the chain of FNAC stores to small boutiques in the middle of the cities, where he was able to assert his identity.
“We have been following the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, through the tumultuous development of e-mails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "Zacházka", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also released new notebook records commemorating a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifys its products: bags, diaries, pencils, notebook cases... The brand is expanding to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment funds of SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the proportion of unemployed disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today is the 15th week of employment for disabled people.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled people is even twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
"No, underscores Eric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes a Week for the Employment of the Disabled."
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that many obstacles remain for unemployed disabled people before they start working.
They are elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma, and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to work and which constitute the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
It remains unspoken, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the managers interviewed had a "poor level of knowledge about disabled persons" with an "exaggerated notion of persons in a mobile chair and mental or mental deficiencies".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, give a figure of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which is responsible for charging companies that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of 'fine' enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, Pierre Blanc explains."
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
